[Opening "Alekhine Defence, Timoshenko Variation"]
[Annotator "Greco / James Hurst 2026-06-15"]

1. e4 { Timoshenko Variation: both sides capture all the way through to the
enemy camp. White answers 1...Nf6 with 2.Nc3 rather than the more common
2.e5, and the game soon turns into a race of mutual captures. } 1... Nf6
{ Alekhine Defence. Black invites the e-pawn to overextend. }
2. Nc3 d5 { Black stakes a claim in the centre. }
3. e5 d4 { White advances anyway; Black gains space and the d4-pawn will
shortly drive deep into White's position. }
4. exf6 { White takes the knight; the f-pawn now heads toward the seventh
rank. } 4... dxc3 { Black recaptures on c3, eliminating the Nc3 and creating
a passed c-pawn of its own. The mutual-captures sequence is now in full swing. }
5. fxg7 { White's pawn reaches the seventh rank. } 5... cxd2+
{ Black's c3-pawn captures d2 with check: a pawn on d2 attacks the e1-square
diagonally, putting the white king in check. }
6. Bxd2 { White blocks with the dark-squared bishop. } 6... Bxg7
{ The key result of the variation: Black's dark-squared bishop occupies g7
with nothing in front of it. The g-pawn that would normally block the long
diagonal (a1-h8) has been exchanged away, so the bishop bears down the entire
diagonal from g7 to a1. Black has active piece play as compensation for the
pawn imbalance; White has an extra pawn but a disrupted structure. The position
is sharp and unbalanced. } *
